# Site template standards

## Brand identity

- Put company name, phones, email, socials, `SITE_URL`, and asset filenames in [`site/src/brand/config.js`](site/src/brand/config.js).
- Do not scatter a second copy of those strings in SEO scripts — import from `brand/config.js`.
- [`site/src/legal/constants.js`](site/src/legal/constants.js) may re-export brand values and keep URL helpers (`href`, `absoluteUrl`).
- Marketing copy stays in `site/src/content/`; replace it when cloning a brand (do not invent a CMS in-pass).

## Secrets

- Never put private API keys, HubSpot private tokens, or PATs in `VITE_*` (they ship to the browser).
- Formspree form IDs are public endpoint IDs, not secrets — still do not commit `.env`.
- Mirror backup uses Actions secret `BACKUP_GITHUB_TOKEN` (durable fine-grained PAT). See `site/DEPLOY.md`.

## Lead capture

- Formspree / HubSpot stay **deferred** until the owner explicitly requests wiring.
- Quote form must fail clearly with phone/email when not configured — never fake success.

## Local vs production

- User “deploy” usually means `cd site && npm run dev` → http://localhost:5180/.
- Do not push to GitHub / production without explicit approval.

## Clone workflow

- Follow [`TEMPLATE.md`](TEMPLATE.md): brand config → public assets/CNAME → content/privacy → Pages → Cloudflare headers → smoke.
- Hold Dependabot **major** Actions bumps until SHA re-pin + Pages smoke; npm patch/minor OK when `build` is green.

## Frontend design (marketing pages)

- Preserve Pixel CTA budget and visual language unless the task is a redesign.
- Prefer existing CSS variables; do not introduce purple-on-white / cream-serif-terracotta defaults when creating new brands without a brief.
